1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:28,560
 PASTEVŠEK: Good afternoon all.Thank you for being punctual after lunch.I guess a few degrees lower temperature helped to bring you back.But much more important than that,is our

2
00:00:28,560 --> 00:00:57,120
 keynote speaker.I'm really honoured to chair this session.Claudio is my former colleague and head of department monetary economic department at the BIS.Claudio was at my farewell party a year ago when I retired from the BIS.

3
00:00:57,120 --> 00:01:17,000
 and Claudio himself then retired a few months ago at the end of last year.Claudio,I don't need to say,has been a spiritus moment behind the BIS view

4
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:45,000
 over the past few decades.And the paper that he will present is a perfect type of keynote that we like at this conference because it casts a broad net and looks back and looks forward.In this case at inflation targeting,the monetary framework that has dominated the policy making.

5
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:54,880
 policy making in central banks since the late 1980s since the late 1980s.So Claudia,the floor is yours.Thank you.

6
00:01:54,880 --> 00:02:21,880
 Well thank you to Ravko and thanks to the organisers generally for inviting me as Boris was saying.I you've been inviting me for a long time and I always said no because of the annual economic report but finally after retiring I can do this.The other I think preamble is that my presentation has nothing to do with global supply chains and the great reallocation.So I don't know what the time to do with global supply chains and the great reallocation.So I don't know what the time to do with global supply chains and the global supply chains and the global supply chain.

7
00:02:21,880 --> 00:02:31,760
 So I don't know what the title is there but I hope I don't have to talk about that because then I would have some problems.

8
00:02:31,760 --> 00:02:50,640
 Now rather what I would do,I intend to do also following suggestions with the organisers is to share with you some personal reflections on monetary policy based on my long career at the BIS, more than 30 years.

9
00:02:50,640 --> 00:03:06,520
 What I thought I would do is to stand back and provide a personal perspective on the success and limitations of what has really become the de facto global monetary standard and that is inflation targeting.

10
00:03:06,520 --> 00:03:28,400
 key takeaways from my presentation I would say basically two really first inflation targeting has achieved what it was designed to achieve which is to help deliver an era of price stability across the world and that's no mean feat because we know that price stability is a precondition for longer term prosperity.

11
00:03:28,400 --> 00:03:43,280
 And second and however this is the however part I worry that to be fit for purpose longer term it needs to adapt in ways that probably do not figure that prominently in the current debate.

12
00:03:43,280 --> 00:04:06,280
 And by that I mean more systematic consideration of the long term damage that financial factors can cause to the economy, more systematic consideration of the importance of safety margins in the operation of policy and all this grounded on a clear recognition of what monetary policy can and above all cannot deliver.

13
00:04:06,280 --> 00:04:15,280
 So the road map of my presentation I will briefly recall the success story which is really not the controversial part.

14
00:04:15,280 --> 00:04:20,280
 I will then move on to probe some of the limitations and this is the more controversial part of my presentation.

15
00:04:20,280 --> 00:04:24,280
 I will finally then propose some refinements based on that.

16
00:04:24,280 --> 00:04:35,280
 By the way I don't have any graphs here nor a written sort of set of slides but there is of course a written presentation which is full of slides and full of graphs.

17
00:04:35,280 --> 00:04:41,280
 And which tries to provide some of the background evidence for some of the things that I will be saying.

18
00:04:41,280 --> 00:04:48,280
 But effectively these are things accumulated over many years of work with colleagues at the BIS.

19
00:04:48,280 --> 00:04:52,280
 So let me start the journey with a definition of inflation targeting.

20
00:04:52,280 --> 00:04:57,280
 And I would say for the current purposes I will basically use three key features.

21
00:04:57,280 --> 00:05:00,280
 First of all numerical targets for inflation.

22
00:05:00,280 --> 00:05:07,280
 Second doing away with intermediate targets such as credit monetary aggregates or even the exchange rate.

23
00:05:07,280 --> 00:05:13,280
 And finally a supporting communication strategy to strengthen transparency and accountability.

24
00:05:13,280 --> 00:05:20,280
 Now looking back inflation targeting had a hesitant and I would say inauspicious beginning.

25
00:05:20,280 --> 00:05:25,280
 Because it had really been adopted by countries that had tried everything else and it hadn't worked.

26
00:05:25,280 --> 00:05:28,280
 So I am thinking of New Zealand, Canada and the UK.

27
00:05:28,280 --> 00:05:35,280
 It was a little bit like if you want to be uncharitable, which I won't be, you could say that it was out of desperation.

28
00:05:35,280 --> 00:05:44,280
 Now moreover compared with inflation targeting strategies, it certainly represented a certain leap of faith.

29
00:05:44,280 --> 00:05:52,280
 I remember at the time the whole debate in monetary economics was about how to achieve a given inflation objective, if you like.

30
00:05:52,280 --> 00:05:56,280
 Given the loose link between instruments and final objectives.

31
00:05:56,280 --> 00:05:57,280
 So the control problem.

32
00:05:57,280 --> 00:06:09,280
 Now inflation targeting in contrast basically did away with these intermediate objectives, exchange rates, monetary aggregates, whatever.

33
00:06:09,280 --> 00:06:10,280
 And was silent about these issues.

34
00:06:10,280 --> 00:06:21,280
 It was basically postulating a direct and stable link between your instrument, your short term interest rate and overnight rate, and your ultimate objective, which is inflation.

35
00:06:21,280 --> 00:06:28,280
 Now prima facie you could say that it was a case of if you cannot will the means, well, will the end.

36
00:06:28,280 --> 00:06:36,280
 Now despite, despite this inauspicious beginning, inflation targeting has clearly gone from strength to strength.

37
00:06:36,280 --> 00:06:39,280
 It has been adopted widely across the world.

38
00:06:39,280 --> 00:06:48,280
 It has passed what I would define as the no regret test, that is no country has abandoned the regime after having adopted it.

39
00:06:48,280 --> 00:06:53,280
 And judged by its explicit objective, it has been a success story.

40
00:06:53,280 --> 00:07:04,280
 Inflation is generally stable, has been generally been stable across the world and central banks have been able to bring it down following the surprising surge post COVID.

41
00:07:04,280 --> 00:07:08,280
 Now to be sure, circumstances did help along the way.

42
00:07:08,280 --> 00:07:11,280
 I will say more about that in a minute.

43
00:07:11,280 --> 00:07:19,280
 But I think that the role of inflation targeting in hardwiring a low inflation regime, I think it's undeniable.

44
00:07:19,280 --> 00:07:26,280
 But what about the challenges that inflation targeting has faced over this long period?

45
00:07:26,280 --> 00:07:39,280
 The key question that I think we should all ask is to what extent those challenges are exogenous to the regime itself or at least in part the result of how the regime has been operated.

46
00:07:39,280 --> 00:07:46,280
 And I think forming a view about this key question is essential if one wants to identify refinements going forward.

47
00:07:46,280 --> 00:07:55,280
 Now my thesis is that some of the challenges are in part, in part the result of the specific regime's operation.

48
00:07:55,280 --> 00:07:57,280
 And I will focus on two.

49
00:07:57,280 --> 00:07:59,280
 One is the great financial crisis.

50
00:07:59,280 --> 00:08:05,280
 And the other are the difficulties in pushing inflation back to point targets following the great financial crisis.

51
00:08:05,280 --> 00:08:16,280
 And connecting these two challenges is what I would call a historic loss in the room for policy maneuver that monetary policy has suffered even before the COVID crisis struck.

52
00:08:16,280 --> 00:08:26,280
 We know that in nominal terms, interest rates had never been as low, indeed in negative terms, in negative territory since records had begun.

53
00:08:26,280 --> 00:08:33,280
 In real terms, they had been negative for even longer than what they had been during the great inflation era.

54
00:08:33,280 --> 00:08:40,280
 And central bank balance sheets had reached peaks previously approximated only during wars.

55
00:08:40,280 --> 00:08:45,280
 Now, the COVID crisis simply exacerbated this condition.

56
00:08:45,280 --> 00:08:47,280
 So let me say a few words about each.

57
00:08:47,280 --> 00:08:51,280
 First of all, the pre-great financial crisis phase.

58
00:08:51,280 --> 00:08:59,280
 Now, when inflation targeting was first adopted, people worried very much as to whether it would be able to withstand negative supply-side shocks.

59
00:08:59,280 --> 00:09:05,280
 Of course, these are the shocks that create the trickiest political economy and economic problems for central banks,

60
00:09:05,280 --> 00:09:08,280
 because we know they raise inflation and reduce output.

61
00:09:08,280 --> 00:09:14,280
 Instead, actually, I was more concerned with threats coming from the financial side.

62
00:09:14,280 --> 00:09:18,280
 In particular, I was worried about financial instability.

63
00:09:18,280 --> 00:09:24,280
 And in that context, about positives, not negatives, but positive supply-side shocks.

64
00:09:24,280 --> 00:09:27,280
 Or better put, positive supply-side forces.

65
00:09:27,280 --> 00:09:30,280
 So why am I concerned?

66
00:09:30,280 --> 00:09:41,280
 Well, as inflation targeting spread, the economic landscape was fundamentally changing in the wake of deeper policy-induced tectonic forces.

67
00:09:41,280 --> 00:09:53,280
 On the one hand, financial liberalisation was providing bigger scope for disruptive financial expansions and contractions, what I would call financial cycles.

68
00:09:53,280 --> 00:10:03,280
 That is, the self-reinforcing shifts in credit, asset prices and risk-taking, that create expansions that are actually subsequently followed by contractions.

69
00:10:03,280 --> 00:10:13,280
 And on the other hand, the globalisation of the real side of the economy, and we've heard a little bit about that before, this positive supply-side force,

70
00:10:13,280 --> 00:10:19,280
 had started blowing powerful disinflationary tailwinds across the world.

71
00:10:19,280 --> 00:10:27,280
 Think of the integration of former communist countries and China into world trade, and the opening up of emerging market economies.

72
00:10:27,280 --> 00:10:39,280
 This was adding a huge number of lower-cost workers to the world's effective labour force, transforming the wage-price nexus, which is the real engine of inflation.

73
00:10:39,280 --> 00:10:51,280
 Now, in that context, let me stress, the inflation targeting regime could inadvertently accommodate the build-up of financial imbalances,

74
00:10:51,280 --> 00:10:57,280
 because there would be no incentive for monetary policy to tighten as long as inflation remained under control.

75
00:10:57,280 --> 00:11:05,280
 Especially, especially since inflation targeting dispensed with any quantitative aggregate or quantitative intermediate target.

76
00:11:05,280 --> 00:11:11,280
 Indeed, if you look closely at the data, in fact, you don't really need to look at it that closely,

77
00:11:11,280 --> 00:11:17,280
 a subtle change in the nature of the business cycle was taking place starting in the mid-1980s,

78
00:11:17,280 --> 00:11:26,280
 from what I would call financial inflation-induced to financial cycle-induced recessions, at least in advanced economies.

79
00:11:26,280 --> 00:11:34,280
 What I mean by that, until then, the typical trigger of a downturn was the monetary tightening to quell inflation.

80
00:11:34,280 --> 00:11:41,280
 In the meantime, indicators of the financial cycle were not really moving that much.

81
00:11:41,280 --> 00:11:51,280
 Thereafter, inflation would not increase that much, which meant that monetary policy would not have to increase, tighten that much,

82
00:11:51,280 --> 00:11:58,280
 but very large financial expansions were giving way to financial contractions.

83
00:11:58,280 --> 00:12:02,280
 And, of course, the great financial crisis is the most spectacular case,

84
00:12:02,280 --> 00:12:08,280
 but if you look at the downturns of the 1990s, they were already qualitatively of that nature.

85
00:12:08,280 --> 00:12:16,280
 I'm thinking of the full-blown crisis in the Nordic countries, or indeed of the banking strains in the United States.

86
00:12:16,280 --> 00:12:26,280
 So, put differently, inflation became an unreliable signal of the sustainability of economic expansions.

87
00:12:26,280 --> 00:12:29,280
 The build-up of financial imbalances was taking over that role.

88
00:12:29,280 --> 00:12:41,280
 Now, importantly, the unreliability of inflation, as a signal, was, of course, also transmitted, if you like, to R*.

89
00:12:41,280 --> 00:12:51,280
 precisely at a time when R* was inevitably rising in policy making, as intermediate targets had been abandoned.

90
00:12:51,280 --> 00:12:58,280
 Now, we know that R* is defined as the short-term, short-term real interest rate, which is consistent with output of potential,

91
00:12:58,280 --> 00:13:06,280
 and inflation stable, and therefore, typically at target, absent business cycle disturbances, that is, in steady state.

92
00:13:06,280 --> 00:13:13,280
 So, a common practice at the time, when inflation turned out to be lower than expected,

93
00:13:13,280 --> 00:13:19,280
 was basically to raise estimate of potential output, and therefore to reduce estimates of the natural rate,

94
00:13:19,280 --> 00:13:26,280
 which meant that if you wanted to keep the monetary policy stance constant, you had to reduce interest rates.

95
00:13:26,280 --> 00:13:34,280
 Now, you can see that over time, over time, over successive business and financial cycles,

96
00:13:34,280 --> 00:13:38,280
 this could actually reduce the room for policy manoeuvre.

97
00:13:38,280 --> 00:13:43,280
 interest rates would tend to fall, financial imbalances would tend to increase,

98
00:13:43,280 --> 00:13:51,280
 and then these financial imbalances would ultimately usher in financial cycle recessions,

99
00:13:51,280 --> 00:13:56,280
 financial instability, financial induced downturns, which tend to be deeper,

100
00:13:56,280 --> 00:14:00,280
 and whose recoveries from are actually lengthier.

101
00:14:00,280 --> 00:14:05,280
 Which meant that interest rates had to be lower for longer,

102
00:14:05,280 --> 00:14:12,280
 as the debt overhand was absorbed, and the capital misallocation corrected.

103
00:14:12,280 --> 00:14:15,280
 Think of the big booms in the property markets.

104
00:14:15,280 --> 00:14:22,280
 So, in this sense, you could see how low rates, in a way, could beget lower rates.

105
00:14:22,280 --> 00:14:26,280
 What about the post-GFC phase?

106
00:14:26,280 --> 00:14:32,280
 Well, in the post-GFC phase, I worry in particular that over-reliance on the concept of R*

107
00:14:32,280 --> 00:14:36,280
 could actually further reduce the room for policy manoeuvre.

108
00:14:36,280 --> 00:14:44,280
 And this paradoxically, paradoxically, as a result of attempts to regain that room for policy manoeuvre.

109
00:14:44,280 --> 00:14:49,280
 Remember, this was a key consideration in the review of policy frameworks.

110
00:14:49,280 --> 00:14:55,280
 And here, the notion that R* is exogenous to monetary policy is key.

111
00:14:55,280 --> 00:15:00,280
 Because if the equilibrium real interest rate is exogenous, entirely exogenous,

112
00:15:00,280 --> 00:15:06,280
 then the only way to regain room for policy manoeuvre on a durable basis is to raise inflation.

113
00:15:06,280 --> 00:15:11,280
 That means reducing interest rates today in order to be able to raise them in the future.

114
00:15:11,280 --> 00:15:22,280
 Which means losing room for policy manoeuvre for certain today in the expectation of regaining it in the future.

115
00:15:22,280 --> 00:15:28,280
 Now, you could see the risk of this strategy is that if inflation does not respond sufficiently to monetary policy,

116
00:15:28,280 --> 00:15:33,280
 you would end up losing as opposed to regaining that room for policy manoeuvre.

117
00:15:33,280 --> 00:15:42,280
 Now, as it turned out, central banks did struggle to push inflation back to point targets, even as the economies recovered.

118
00:15:42,280 --> 00:15:49,280
 Although, importantly, I think the shortfalls always remained contained within a handful of basis points.

119
00:15:49,280 --> 00:15:58,280
 Moreover, concerns about the de-anchoring of expectations and ultimately deflation provided an additional reason to push harder.

120
00:15:58,280 --> 00:16:05,280
 Now, I see at least two reasons why central banks struggled to push inflation up.

121
00:16:05,280 --> 00:16:15,280
 First is that the impact of easing of monetary policy on aggregate demand may exhibit diminishing returns after a certain point.

122
00:16:15,280 --> 00:16:25,280
 After all, if the textbooks are right, monetary policy mainly operates by bringing demand from the future to the present.

123
00:16:25,280 --> 00:16:30,280
 And surely there must be limits to that process.

124
00:16:30,280 --> 00:16:41,280
 Moreover, more prosaically, if you like, low for long interest rates tend to sap back bank profitability and therefore banks' credit generating capacity.

125
00:16:41,280 --> 00:16:45,280
 And there is considerable evidence, I think, to that effect.

126
00:16:45,280 --> 00:16:55,280
 Now, the second reason is that inflation may respond less to aggregate demand pressures when inflation settles at a low level.

127
00:16:55,280 --> 00:17:00,280
 Now, one possible explanation, which is very specific to the period that we saw,

128
00:17:00,280 --> 00:17:08,280
 is that the globalization tailwinds turned into headwinds when central banks were trying to push inflation up.

129
00:17:08,280 --> 00:17:18,280
 But a more general explanation, and I think this is the more important point, has to do with the inherent properties of inflation in a low inflation regime.

130
00:17:18,280 --> 00:17:21,280
 So, let me develop that a little bit.

131
00:17:21,280 --> 00:17:34,280
 Now, recent work with colleagues, and Marco is one of them, has confirmed that inflation behaves very differently in low and high inflation regimes.

132
00:17:34,280 --> 00:17:41,280
 In a low inflation regime, inflation exhibits some certain self-stabilizing properties.

133
00:17:41,280 --> 00:17:51,280
 That's because what we measure as inflation is largely the result of a myriad of idiosyncratic or sector-specific price changes.

134
00:17:51,280 --> 00:17:55,280
 That is, the common component of price changes is quite low.

135
00:17:55,280 --> 00:18:02,280
 And because of their very nature, these changes tend to leave a little imprint on inflation.

136
00:18:02,280 --> 00:18:07,280
 In addition, the link between wages and prices tends to be quite loose.

137
00:18:07,280 --> 00:18:10,280
 Now, what's the underlying reason for all this?

138
00:18:10,280 --> 00:18:21,280
 Now, the explanation that I personally find most appealing is that when inflation is low, it does not materially influence people's behavior.

139
00:18:21,280 --> 00:18:33,280
 These economic agents, and by here I mean specific, not so much financial markets, but I do mean labor and firms, become rationally inattentive.

140
00:18:33,280 --> 00:18:35,280
 And I will come back to this.

141
00:18:35,280 --> 00:18:41,280
 By contrast, in a high inflation regime, no such self-stabilizing properties are at work.

142
00:18:41,280 --> 00:18:47,280
 The common component of price changes is higher, and wages and prices tend to be more tightly linked.

143
00:18:47,280 --> 00:18:54,280
 So that shock to sector-specific prices tend to turn into persistent inflation much more easily.

144
00:18:54,280 --> 00:19:08,280
 Now, critically, the fact that the small common component of price changes, when inflation is low, reduces the responsiveness of inflation to adjustments in the monetary policy stance.

145
00:19:08,280 --> 00:19:20,280
 And that is because intuitively, changes in the stands work precisely through that component, which is the one which is more closely related to aggregate demand and to exchange rates.

146
00:19:20,280 --> 00:19:25,280
 And again, there is quite a bit of empirical evidence that confirms that very simple intuition.

147
00:19:25,280 --> 00:19:41,280
 So to recap, central banks' reaction function in inflation targeting regimes has arguably contributed to the progressive loss in the room for policy maneuver before the COVID crisis.

148
00:19:41,280 --> 00:19:54,280
 At each point in time, central banks were taking as an exogenous interest rate was, in fact, to some extent, the result of their previous actions.

149
00:19:54,280 --> 00:20:04,280
 So ultimately, and I was concerned about this, this was raising the risk of a debt trap, whereby interest rates would decline over time.

150
00:20:04,280 --> 00:20:15,280
 And this is the trend, debts would basically go up, and this would make it harder for the central banks to raise interest rates without creating problems for the real economy.

151
00:20:15,280 --> 00:20:22,280
 Now, all the more so, if we consider what was going on with the public sector debt, as opposed to private sector debt.

152
00:20:22,280 --> 00:20:25,280
 So this is not the financial cycle as such.

153
00:20:25,280 --> 00:20:37,280
 So even pre-COVID, government to debt GDP ratios had reached historical peaks across much of the world, in line with the previous Second World War peaks.

154
00:20:37,280 --> 00:20:49,280
 Now, the financial cycle had a lot to do with this too, and I won't go into that, but basically, sort of raising, giving the appearance that revenues were much stronger than they actually were.

155
00:20:49,280 --> 00:20:57,280
 But as did also, an important factor here was the belief that interest rates would remain low, as far as I could see.

156
00:20:57,280 --> 00:21:04,280
 Now, it took a huge exogenous shock to jolt the system away from its path, at least temporarily.

157
00:21:04,280 --> 00:21:12,280
 Now, to be sure, first central banks and governments had to consume further the room for manoeuvre they had at their disposal to deal with the COVID crisis.

158
00:21:12,280 --> 00:21:20,280
 But then, the unexpected surge in inflation induced a welcome and forceful monetary policy tightening.

159
00:21:20,280 --> 00:21:37,280
 So, central banks did regain room for policy manoeuvre, but at this time, necessarily, given what was going on with the public sector debt, at the expense of governments, which basically saw their interest rate bill balloon.

160
00:21:37,280 --> 00:21:46,280
 Now, the key question going forward, therefore, is whether interest rates will settle as inflation is brought back under control.

161
00:21:46,280 --> 00:21:47,280
 Where will they settle?

162
00:21:47,280 --> 00:21:58,280
 Now, if the analysis is correct, if the analysis is correct, this will partly depend on any further evolution in the inflation targeting regimes themselves.

163
00:21:58,280 --> 00:22:15,280
 Now, at this point, I'm pretty sure that many of you, if not all of you are asking, well, what about the evidence that R* is determined by fundamental slow-moving forces, productivity growth, demographics, income distribution and the like?

164
00:22:15,280 --> 00:22:19,280
 I mean, we know what I would call the usual suspects.

165
00:22:19,280 --> 00:22:21,280
 Well, I think my answer is threefold here.

166
00:22:21,280 --> 00:22:46,280
 First, the previous analysis suggests that monetary policy can easily have a very persistent impact on real interest rates through its impact on financial stability, on the financial system, which for all intents and purposes, for all intents and purposes, are indistinguishable from an impact on R* given how long they last.

167
00:22:46,280 --> 00:22:51,280
 Second, empirical evidence is not as strong as it is normally believed.

168
00:22:51,280 --> 00:23:05,280
 When data and data are allowed to speak, there's really no much evidence of a systematic link between the usual suspects that I mentioned earlier and real interest rates before the mid-1980s.

169
00:23:05,280 --> 00:23:18,280
 And in fact, if the sample is extended back to the 1870s, a robust relationship emerges with respect to monetary policy regimes across time and countries.

170
00:23:18,280 --> 00:23:32,280
 And finally, this suggests to me that the link between real interest rates and output of potential on stable inflation is not really as tight as it is normally believed.

171
00:23:32,280 --> 00:23:51,280
 So, if you like, my hypothesis is that a range of real policy rates can be broadly consistent with such outcomes, even over extended periods.

172
00:23:51,280 --> 00:24:10,280
 So, from this perspective, the very large confidence bands that we see around R* may not so much reflect the fact that a precise relationship is measured imprecisely, but rather the relationship itself is imprecise.

173
00:24:10,280 --> 00:24:15,280
 So, what about possible adjustments to the inflation targeting regime?

174
00:24:15,280 --> 00:24:20,280
 Now, if you buy this analysis, what could those be?

175
00:24:20,280 --> 00:24:26,280
 I think that any such adjustments would need to take into account a number of considerations.

176
00:24:26,280 --> 00:24:29,280
 So, let me mention four here.

177
00:24:29,280 --> 00:24:34,280
 The first is that the framework needs to be robust to alternative possible economic environments.

178
00:24:34,280 --> 00:24:41,280
 And I have a sense that not all the changes that we saw after the COVID crisis took that form.

179
00:24:41,280 --> 00:24:45,280
 And I'm thinking also in particular of what happened at the Fed.

180
00:24:45,280 --> 00:24:50,280
 Arguably, in the years ahead, the world could be structurally more inflationary.

181
00:24:50,280 --> 00:24:57,280
 If deglobalization takes hold, then labor and firms could regain their pricing power.

182
00:24:57,280 --> 00:25:04,280
 Geopolitics, the green transition, and demographic trends may raise more persistent headwinds.

183
00:25:04,280 --> 00:25:12,280
 And high levels of public and also private debt can provide greater incentives to inflate them away.

184
00:25:12,280 --> 00:25:14,280
 So, these are very structural forces.

185
00:25:14,280 --> 00:25:19,280
 But one cannot rule out a return to the pre-COVID environment.

186
00:25:19,280 --> 00:25:23,280
 Inflation is returning back to low levels.

187
00:25:23,280 --> 00:25:33,280
 And wage pressures have so far been remarkably subdued, I would say, given the erosion in real purchasing power

188
00:25:33,280 --> 00:25:39,280
 that took place, surprising erosion in real purchasing power that took place during COVID.

189
00:25:39,280 --> 00:25:44,280
 By the way, in Switzerland, we're already talking about negative interest rates again.

190
00:25:44,280 --> 00:25:47,280
 So, we're back where we started, as it were.

191
00:25:47,280 --> 00:25:54,280
 The second consideration is what I would call the importance of long policy horizons,

192
00:25:54,280 --> 00:25:56,280
 which I don't think I could stress enough.

193
00:25:56,280 --> 00:26:03,280
 We know that long policy horizons are already commonplace and important in the country.

194
00:26:03,280 --> 00:26:08,280
 In the context of inflation control, recall the temptation to boost output in the short run,

195
00:26:08,280 --> 00:26:14,280
 but at the expense of higher inflation longer term, this form of time inconsistency.

196
00:26:14,280 --> 00:26:20,280
 But then the financial cycle can raise a more insidious form of time inconsistency.

197
00:26:20,280 --> 00:26:28,280
 And that is because the financial cycle tends to be much longer than how the business cycle is traditionally,

198
00:26:28,280 --> 00:26:33,280
 let me stress, traditionally measured, the kind of statistical filters that we use for that,

199
00:26:33,280 --> 00:26:37,280
 which, by some estimates, is about twice as long.

200
00:26:37,280 --> 00:26:45,280
 It is as if the emergence of the financial cycle had slowed down economic time in relation to calendar time,

201
00:26:45,280 --> 00:26:53,280
 so that the time that the economic forces that really matter effectively play themselves out over a longer period.

202
00:26:53,280 --> 00:27:02,280
 But in fact, actually applying statistical filters similar to those that we normally apply to output,

203
00:27:02,280 --> 00:27:12,280
 sorry, to the financial cycle to output, actually unveils, reveals that there is also a medium term business cycle

204
00:27:12,280 --> 00:27:15,280
 that moves remarkably in sync with the financial cycle.

205
00:27:15,280 --> 00:27:21,280
 And I think that we haven't done enough work in that area in general.

206
00:27:21,280 --> 00:27:22,280
 Third consideration.

207
00:27:22,280 --> 00:27:30,280
 I think it's the need to incorporate systematically the importance of safety margins or buffers in the conduct of policy,

208
00:27:30,280 --> 00:27:36,280
 because economies operating without safety margins are vulnerable to both the inevitable next recession

209
00:27:36,280 --> 00:27:39,280
 and to unexpected shocks such as the COVID crisis.

210
00:27:39,280 --> 00:27:47,280
 Now, in all walks of life, in all walks of life, the need to retain safety margins is an explicit guide to action.

211
00:27:47,280 --> 00:27:50,280
 Why should really it be different from monetary policy?

212
00:27:50,280 --> 00:27:55,280
 If something is valuable, one should be willing to pay a price for it.

213
00:27:55,280 --> 00:28:04,280
 And the final consideration, I think it's essential to have a realistic view of what monetary policy can and cannot deliver.

214
00:28:04,280 --> 00:28:12,280
 As long as it is prepared to pay the price, monetary policy can bring inflation down and avoiding it becoming entrenched.

215
00:28:12,280 --> 00:28:19,280
 As long as it has fiscal backing, monetary policy can stabilise the financial system at times of stress,

216
00:28:19,280 --> 00:28:25,280
 even if solvency is at stake in playing its traditional role of the lender of last resort

217
00:28:25,280 --> 00:28:29,280
 and increasingly market maker or buyer of last resort.

218
00:28:29,280 --> 00:28:40,280
 And as long as prudential policy is supportive, monetary policy can help to restrain financial imbalances and constrain their damage.

219
00:28:40,280 --> 00:28:50,280
 But monetary policy cannot fine-tune inflation within basis points and let alone economic activity within narrow ranges,

220
00:28:50,280 --> 00:28:57,280
 nor can it be relied upon indirectly or de facto as an engine of growth.

221
00:28:57,280 --> 00:29:03,280
 Now when I see the financial industry and media razzmatazz surrounding policy decisions,

222
00:29:03,280 --> 00:29:08,280
 I worry that we have long lost that sense of realism.

223
00:29:08,280 --> 00:29:16,280
 And I see a dangerous gap developing between an expectations gap between what monetary policy can deliver

224
00:29:16,280 --> 00:29:18,280
 and what it is expected to deliver.

225
00:29:18,280 --> 00:29:25,280
 This clearly can complicate policy, but ultimately it could even undermine central banks' independence and their legitimacy.

226
00:29:25,280 --> 00:29:31,280
 Now these broad considerations have implications for the objectives and strategies to pursue them

227
00:29:31,280 --> 00:29:33,280
 and for symmetry let me just mention four.

228
00:29:33,280 --> 00:29:43,280
 First is that the first implication is that we need to hardwire a low inflation regime and that should remain a priority.

229
00:29:43,280 --> 00:29:51,280
 I love the behavioural definition of price stability that Volcker and Greenspan gave for the reasons that you heard before,

230
00:29:51,280 --> 00:29:58,280
 which is an environment in which inflation does not materially influence people's behaviour.

231
00:29:58,280 --> 00:30:08,280
 So let me stress, the objective should not be so much stabilising inflation expectations but actually making them irrelevant.

232
00:30:08,280 --> 00:30:16,280
 And I think that when you are operating in a low inflation regime, the expectations of those people that really matter for inflation ultimately,

233
00:30:16,280 --> 00:30:24,280
 you know households, firms, workers and firms, inflation for them becomes largely irrelevant.

234
00:30:24,280 --> 00:30:31,280
 Now this also means by implication that the idea of raising current targets would be a bad idea.

235
00:30:31,280 --> 00:30:44,280
 Quite apart from undermining central banks' credibility, the usual argument, it would endanger this low inflation environment and hence also the self-stabilising properties that inflation has in such an environment.

236
00:30:44,280 --> 00:30:52,280
 Inflation drifting out of the region of rational inattention into the region of sharp focus.

237
00:30:52,280 --> 00:30:58,280
 And then it could also act as a more effective coordinating device for people's decisions.

238
00:30:58,280 --> 00:31:08,280
 Because remember, as the common factor of price changes falls, actually increases with inflation, those price changes become more similar.

239
00:31:08,280 --> 00:31:20,280
 So that inflation becomes more representative of the price indices that each of us as producers or as consumers are facing.

240
00:31:20,280 --> 00:31:30,280
 Now critically this is one reason, not the only reason, but one reason why transitions from low to high inflation regimes tend to be self-reinforcing.

241
00:31:30,280 --> 00:31:44,280
 The second implication, key adjustment would be to have greater tolerance than in the past for moderate, even as persistent, shortfalls of inflation from narrowly defined targets.

242
00:31:44,280 --> 00:31:54,280
 This would help retain the precious room for maneuver that I was talking about before, exploiting the self-stabilising properties of low inflation regimes.

243
00:31:54,280 --> 00:32:00,280
 And would allow central banks to take more systematically into account the longer term damage caused by persistently low interest rates.

244
00:32:00,280 --> 00:32:10,280
 Now implementing such a strategy would require addressing also the so-called deflation bogeyman, as Felstein and Rajan put it.

245
00:32:10,280 --> 00:32:20,280
 If seeing deflation as a kind of red line that once crossed generates self-reinforcing downward spirals in economic activity or a depression trap.

246
00:32:20,280 --> 00:32:26,280
 Neither empirically nor conceptually is the link as strong as often believed.

247
00:32:26,280 --> 00:32:37,280
 Third implication, further thought should be given to how best to use the additional room for maneuver that I mentioned earlier to tackle the financial cycle.

248
00:32:37,280 --> 00:32:41,280
 I have no specific answers here, but just the general direction of travel.

249
00:32:41,280 --> 00:32:44,280
 Lengthening policy horizons as far as possible.

250
00:32:44,280 --> 00:32:52,280
 Upgrading the role of financial conditions, particularly credit aggregates and property prices in policy making as guides to policy.

251
00:32:52,280 --> 00:32:58,280
 And analytically, I would say, a paradigm shift in the way that we think about the business cycle.

252
00:32:58,280 --> 00:33:03,280
 Away from the shock, propagation, return to steady state paradigm.

253
00:33:03,280 --> 00:33:08,280
 To one that sees endogenous fluctuations are being the essence of business cycles.

254
00:33:08,280 --> 00:33:14,280
 Endogenous fluctuations that can be potentially unstable as a result of the role of financial factors.

255
00:33:14,280 --> 00:33:25,280
 And the final implication is to adopt further adjustments designed to preserve and increase the flexibility and safety margins.

256
00:33:25,280 --> 00:33:27,280
 And here I would just mention two.

257
00:33:27,280 --> 00:33:36,280
 One is less reliance on forms of forward guidance that provide specific information about the interest rate path beyond the central bank's reaction function.

258
00:33:36,280 --> 00:33:45,280
 Which can unduly constrain the central bank's nimbleness and also unduly compress risk premia and therefore encourage risk taking.

259
00:33:45,280 --> 00:33:55,280
 And putting a premium on exit strategies whenever central banks take exceptional measures to stabilize the system and the economy.

260
00:33:55,280 --> 00:34:03,280
 Think of the difficulties that central banks have been facing in reducing the historically large and risky balance sheets they have.

261
00:34:03,280 --> 00:34:10,280
 I think that a reasonable principle here would be that central bank balance sheets should be as small and riskless as possible.

262
00:34:10,280 --> 00:34:15,280
 Subject to fulfilling of course central bank mandates effectively.

263
00:34:15,280 --> 00:34:23,280
 But to my mind except possibly for the need to hold foreign exchange reserves for precautionary purposes for some countries around the world.

264
00:34:23,280 --> 00:34:26,280
 Balance sheets can be very, very small.

265
00:34:26,280 --> 00:34:33,280
 Central bank balance sheets should be elastic ready to increase when circumstances required and not large.

266
00:34:33,280 --> 00:34:39,280
 And given the economic and political economic costs of large balance sheets the initial size is a hindrance.

267
00:34:39,280 --> 00:34:41,280
 It's not a plus.

268
00:34:41,280 --> 00:34:44,280
 So what kind of regime do I have in mind?

269
00:34:44,280 --> 00:34:48,280
 Well it's one where the central bank keeps a sharp focus on the medium term.

270
00:34:48,280 --> 00:34:58,280
 seeking to ensure that the financial side of the economy which it influences, the central bank influences and through which it operates.

271
00:34:58,280 --> 00:35:06,280
 Does not end up derailing the economy through inflation or the financial instability broadly defined.

272
00:35:06,280 --> 00:35:13,280
 So if you like central bank should simply set the monetary preconditions for sustainable growth.

273
00:35:13,280 --> 00:35:19,280
 But that do not end up being relied upon as the engines of that growth.

274
00:35:19,280 --> 00:35:26,280
 a regime where the operational definition of inflation target is consistent with that overarching objective.

275
00:35:26,280 --> 00:35:32,280
 That is low enough so that inflation does not materially influence people's behaviour.

276
00:35:32,280 --> 00:35:41,280
 But flexible enough to allow the central bank to take into account the financial forces that can generate longer term damage to the real economy.

277
00:35:41,280 --> 00:35:54,280
 And a regime where the central bank's reaction function calls for forceful responses when inflation threatens on the upside because of the self-reinforcing nature of the transitions to high inflation.

278
00:35:54,280 --> 00:35:59,280
 But allows for greater tolerance for moderate even if persistent shortfalls of inflation from target.

279
00:35:59,280 --> 00:36:05,280
 And this goes back to the self-stabilizing properties of inflation and the deflation bogeyman.

280
00:36:05,280 --> 00:36:10,280
 So a couple of concluding reflections here.

281
00:36:10,280 --> 00:36:20,280
 Looking forward, I do worry that the toughest challenges for monetary policy and indeed for inflation targeting are still to come.

282
00:36:20,280 --> 00:36:27,280
 For one, the political environment is becoming less conducive to a stability oriented monetary policy.

283
00:36:27,280 --> 00:36:35,280
 There are growing pressures on the central banks who take a short term view and the demands on them are growing.

284
00:36:35,280 --> 00:36:47,280
 And in such an environment, institutional safeguards such as central bank independence become all the more precious but of course they can only take you, help you up to a point.

285
00:36:47,280 --> 00:36:57,280
 Moreover, I would not, I would not take too much comfort from the recent rather painless reduction in inflation that we have seen.

286
00:36:57,280 --> 00:37:07,280
 I think circumstances were simply extraordinary and I believe the future fights are likely to involve bigger costs as they did in the past.

287
00:37:07,280 --> 00:37:10,280
 Especially if the world becomes less globalized.

288
00:37:10,280 --> 00:37:17,280
 And if firms and workers in that world regain their purchasing power and their pricing power in general.

289
00:37:17,280 --> 00:37:24,280
 So that we see greater resistance to the erosion of purchasing power and compression of profit margins.

290
00:37:24,280 --> 00:37:35,280
 In addition and closely related, the sustainability of fiscal trajectories is a major threat.

291
00:37:35,280 --> 00:37:46,280
 As we actually said in the annual economic report a couple of years ago, probably the biggest long term threat to macroeconomic and financial stability in the years ahead in the medium term.

292
00:37:46,280 --> 00:37:52,280
 And therefore ultimately a threat to the inflation targeting regime itself.

293
00:37:52,280 --> 00:37:55,280
 Monetary and fiscal policy are joined at the hip.

294
00:37:55,280 --> 00:38:01,280
 And there are clear limits to what monetary policy can do if fiscal policy is out of kilter.

295
00:38:01,280 --> 00:38:09,280
 Both policies have to operate, if you like, in a certain region of stability, which is consistent with sustainable growth.

296
00:38:09,280 --> 00:38:15,280
 Now, by the way, these threats are also likely to make the adjustments that I proposed even less likely.

297
00:38:15,280 --> 00:38:17,280
 I am clear eyed about that.

298
00:38:17,280 --> 00:38:22,280
 But I think that inflation targeting regimes cannot stand still.

299
00:38:22,280 --> 00:38:28,280
 Inflation targeting does not represent the end of monetary policy history, as it were.

300
00:38:28,280 --> 00:38:33,280
 It is just one, if exceptionally long, chapter in that history.

301
00:38:33,280 --> 00:38:34,280
 Thank you very much.

302
00:38:34,280 --> 00:38:44,280
 Thank you, Claudia.

303
00:38:44,280 --> 00:39:02,280
 To help us kick off the discussion, we have two excellent colleagues to introduce to what they think about

304
00:39:02,280 --> 00:39:05,280
 about this range of topics.

305
00:39:05,280 --> 00:39:12,280
 So, first, Vedran Šošić from Croatia National Bank, chief economist of the HNB.

306
00:39:12,280 --> 00:39:14,280
 Thank you, Dubravko.

307
00:39:14,280 --> 00:39:20,280
 Actually, Thorsten got scared when there was a different title of the paper

308
00:39:20,280 --> 00:39:23,280
 and Claudio was sure what he's going to present.

309
00:39:23,280 --> 00:39:30,280
 I also think there was a bit of a mix-up with me also when someone tells me to provide introductory comments.

310
00:39:30,280 --> 00:39:37,280
 I usually assume that it's before the speech and that it needs to contain as few spoilers as possible.

311
00:39:37,280 --> 00:39:50,280
 So, I had a version of the speech with no spoilers, almost no spoilers whatsoever, but during Claudio's speech I have added a few spoilers, which are not spoilers after the speech.

312
00:39:50,280 --> 00:40:02,280
 So, Dubravko said that Claudio spent decades at BIS, and actually those are almost four decades, just to make it clear.

313
00:40:02,280 --> 00:40:17,280
 And for BIS, if you ask CHET GPT about BIS, CHET GPT would say that BIS is an institution that you need to visit after you get a diagnosis from the IMF to get a second opinion.

314
00:40:17,280 --> 00:40:29,280
 And this second opinion that you get from BIS is not something that you want to see, but you certainly need to see this second opinion.

315
00:40:29,280 --> 00:40:44,280
 And also, CHET GPT would say even in a bit more poetic fashion that BIS is the place where economic orthodoxy goes not to die, but to be gently, thoroughly, and respectfully interrogated.

316
00:40:44,280 --> 00:40:59,280
 And Claudio, Claudio is very central, we heard that he was very central in making BIS such an institution, and he did, repeated such a feat today again, on inflation targeting.

317
00:40:59,280 --> 00:41:10,280
 So, for those who did not guess, now you know the inviting Claudio to speak about inflation targeting, here is a bit like inviting Nietzsche to a wellness retreat.

318
00:41:10,280 --> 00:41:19,280
 So, you know it won't be light, it won't be easy, but by the end you'll probably question your entire belief system, and maybe your inflation target too.

319
00:41:19,280 --> 00:41:29,280
 Now, our romance, the central bank's romance with inflation targeting regime has had its rocky moment.

320
00:41:29,280 --> 00:41:42,280
 Claudio said that we had ups and downs, and particularly, he particularly mentioned two moments, the financial crisis, and more recently when inflation decided to make a dramatic post-pandemic comeback.

321
00:41:42,280 --> 00:41:52,280
 But, like any good co-dependent relationship, we kept patching things up and pretending that everything is fine.

322
00:41:52,280 --> 00:41:56,280
 Claudio is not here to recommend us cosmetic fixes.

323
00:41:56,280 --> 00:42:03,280
 He is asking whether it's time not to stop applying patches and to consider a full relationship with inflation targeting.

324
00:42:03,280 --> 00:42:11,280
 So, he wants us to zoom out, to look beyond the short term, to confront whether our very elegant, intellectually elegant,

325
00:42:11,280 --> 00:42:19,280
 but occasionally a bit not fully functional monetary framework is due for some, in his opinion, long overdue therapy.

326
00:42:19,280 --> 00:42:29,280
 And, as always, the central elements of his financial cycles, macro financial imbalances, and always looking through the long-term lens.

327
00:42:29,280 --> 00:42:37,280
 And, brace yourself for this, he even dares to question the 2% inflation target as the monetary version of Nirvana.

328
00:42:37,280 --> 00:42:45,280
 So, he thinks that it's more or less just a number we all agreed upon because it looks very nice in our communiques.

329
00:42:45,280 --> 00:42:56,280
 So, and this, his talk was especially well targeted for central bankers, because we know that central bankers that attend Dubrovnik conference,

330
00:42:56,280 --> 00:42:59,280
 they fall squarely into the Marxist camp.

331
00:42:59,280 --> 00:43:04,280
 Of course, not Karl Marx, but Groucho Marx, as Groucho Marx famously said.

332
00:43:04,280 --> 00:43:11,280
 And, Randy keeps reminding us each and every year, those are my principles, and if you don't like them, well, I have others.

333
00:43:11,280 --> 00:43:22,280
 And, Claudio is, you know, central bankers care about their principles, and in this Groucho Marxist fashion, Claudio offers us a wholly fresh set of principles,

334
00:43:22,280 --> 00:43:30,280
 which are intellectually sound, policy relevant, and probably annoying to many of our orthodox colleagues.

335
00:43:30,280 --> 00:43:37,280
 So, this was not a gentle policy talk with bullet points and the Basel 3 footnotes and zero surprises.

336
00:43:37,280 --> 00:43:43,280
 So, our assumptions about monetary policy framework got poked, prodded, politely dismantled.

337
00:43:43,280 --> 00:43:54,280
 So, just to add a bit more on my introductory remarks, I want to say that Claudio's ideas are gaining, slowly gaining, some of his ideas are gaining traction.

338
00:43:54,280 --> 00:43:59,280
 For example, the idea that R-Star isn't endogenous to monetary policy.

339
00:43:59,280 --> 00:44:02,280
 Isabel had a speech about a year ago, Rising Star.

340
00:44:02,280 --> 00:44:09,280
 She quoted Hildebrandt's paper from 2023, and also quoted a different paper from Claudio,

341
00:44:09,280 --> 00:44:22,280
 and Hildebrandt basically concluded that long-term interest rates are just mostly around, in a very short window, around the Fed meeting.

342
00:44:22,280 --> 00:44:31,280
 So, basically they adjust on, after Central Bank says what it thinks, and then financial markets adjust their long-term view of the economy.

343
00:44:31,280 --> 00:44:38,280
 And with the ECB, I think it's not, I guess you have repeated the exercise, and you did not find similar relations.

344
00:44:38,280 --> 00:44:40,280
 At least we didn't find anything similar.

345
00:44:40,280 --> 00:44:47,280
 The second very important element for me is the complementarity between monetary and macroprudential policy.

346
00:44:47,280 --> 00:44:56,280
 I mean, initially, the macroprudential policy was set up as a wholly independent policy with an independent goal.

347
00:44:56,280 --> 00:45:01,280
 And for us, for example, in Croatia, it was not a new one.

348
00:45:01,280 --> 00:45:10,280
 I mean, for us, the monetary and macroprudential policy has been integrated even before we knew that the macroprudential policy was called the macroprudential policy.

349
00:45:10,280 --> 00:45:14,280
 And this is seeping more and more into mainstream thinking.

350
00:45:14,280 --> 00:45:20,280
 For example, ECB in the last monetary policy review five years ago acknowledged these links,

351
00:45:20,280 --> 00:45:29,280
 and now it has integrated some of these spillovers between monetary and macroprudential policies in the policy framework.

352
00:45:29,280 --> 00:45:34,280
 IMF is even more advanced with the integrated policy framework.

353
00:45:34,280 --> 00:45:40,280
 So the very specific look at spillovers between monetary and macroprudential policies.

354
00:45:40,280 --> 00:45:48,280
 And some of the advanced economies become more like US, for example, becoming a bit more like emerging market economies.

355
00:45:48,280 --> 00:45:53,280
 The central bankers' thinking may move a bit further into this direction.

356
00:45:53,280 --> 00:46:04,280
 So we may start thinking about more and more about monetary macroprudential policies as complements.

357
00:46:04,280 --> 00:46:11,280
 What I don't like is the notion that structural factors are not important for R*.

358
00:46:11,280 --> 00:46:14,280
 So that's something I like a bit less.

359
00:46:14,280 --> 00:46:20,280
 We know there is a research about the impact of demography on R*.

360
00:46:20,280 --> 00:46:23,280
 It shows that the relationship is very complex.

361
00:46:23,280 --> 00:46:25,280
 It's non-linear.

362
00:46:25,280 --> 00:46:28,280
 Even if you hold everything else constant.

363
00:46:28,280 --> 00:46:30,280
 And we know that everything else is not constant.

364
00:46:30,280 --> 00:46:35,280
 For example, as people, as our life expectancy increases,

365
00:46:35,280 --> 00:46:38,280
 older people start to save more, more and more.

366
00:46:38,280 --> 00:46:41,280
 So this is a very dynamic relationship.

367
00:46:41,280 --> 00:46:49,280
 And I would advise not to ditch any attempt to understand the terminants of R*,

368
00:46:49,280 --> 00:47:00,280
 but rather to try to better understand these factors, including the balance between exogenous and endogenous determinants of R*,

369
00:47:00,280 --> 00:47:02,280
 endogenous and exogenous to monetary policy.

370
00:47:02,280 --> 00:47:12,280
 For some ideas, it may be even harder, for example, to abandoning point targets.

371
00:47:12,280 --> 00:47:17,280
 The Fed now has some flexibility, the making up in their strategy.

372
00:47:17,280 --> 00:47:21,280
 And their comments have not been seen very favorable, this making up strategy.

373
00:47:21,280 --> 00:47:25,280
 So I think they may be even moving further to point targets.

374
00:47:25,280 --> 00:47:34,280
 So the central banks may need a bit more persuading to start thinking about point targets.

375
00:47:34,280 --> 00:47:38,280
 Also, Claudio touches upon our modeling framework.

376
00:47:38,280 --> 00:47:42,280
 And we are thinking hard on how to improve our modeling frameworks, our models.

377
00:47:42,280 --> 00:47:48,280
 We know that they are less than perfect, even given what we have experienced over the past five years,

378
00:47:48,280 --> 00:47:50,280
 that there may be ways to improve.

379
00:47:50,280 --> 00:47:53,280
 So we have some things in our shopping cart.

380
00:47:53,280 --> 00:47:58,280
 For example, we have Hank models, heterogeneous agents models,

381
00:47:58,280 --> 00:48:02,280
 which are more complex, which can give rise to nonlinear dynamics.

382
00:48:02,280 --> 00:48:07,280
 We have various satellite models that we use to cross-check our workhorse models.

383
00:48:07,280 --> 00:48:16,280
 So I would say that Claudio is knocking on open doors on the improvement of modeling framework.

384
00:48:16,280 --> 00:48:20,280
 And just one more point on balance sheets.

385
00:48:20,280 --> 00:48:27,280
 Well, we all know that profitability is not a key goal for central banks,

386
00:48:27,280 --> 00:48:30,280
 but it may get harder and harder to accomplish for us.

387
00:48:30,280 --> 00:48:36,280
 For example, if demand for cash substantially decrease with the advent of non-cash payments.

388
00:48:36,280 --> 00:48:39,280
 So we are in our senior region cash.

389
00:48:39,280 --> 00:48:47,280
 So then if we move on a more permanent basis into negative profit and loss account,

390
00:48:47,280 --> 00:48:53,280
 then we may really start to think that profitability is important for us.

391
00:48:53,280 --> 00:48:54,280
 So that's it.

392
00:48:54,280 --> 00:48:54,280
 So thank you, Claudio, for your remarks.

393
00:48:54,280 --> 00:48:55,280
 Thank you.

394
00:48:55,280 --> 00:48:56,280
 Thank you.

395
00:48:56,280 --> 00:48:57,280
 Vedran and Thursten.

