00:52:31,280 --> 00:52:33,280
 and eventually they got it right.

437
00:52:33,280 --> 00:52:44,280
 The one thing that they also pointed out already was that the monetary policy back then, inflation targeting, did not take into account asset price inflation.

438
00:52:44,280 --> 00:52:47,280
 And that was a big discussion back then, I remember that.

439
00:52:47,280 --> 00:52:53,280
 And there was, of course, the other thing which was called a Greenspan put, and then turned into a Bernanke put, and so on.

440
00:52:53,280 --> 00:52:59,280
 You know, with every new federal chair, the put gets a new name, a new first name.

441
00:52:59,280 --> 00:53:11,280
 And, of course, this link between, number one, not taking into account the asset price inflation, and providing this put kind of promising to mop up the mess afterwards,

442
00:53:11,280 --> 00:53:18,280
 so the moral hazard part of it, of course, that also kind of contributed ultimately to what we've seen in 2008.

443
00:53:18,280 --> 00:53:27,280
 So that's one, and so you could say, so my explanation is not that you focus on our star, I was supposed to mention only once,

444
00:53:27,280 --> 00:53:39,280
 but it's also about this kind of more limited focus of inflation targeting, I guess you could argue, or not taking into account the risk-taking channel of monetary policy.

445
00:53:39,280 --> 00:53:50,280
 Now, on the other hand, the post-global financial crisis, so in Europe, I mean, it wasn't a deflation bogeyman, I would say,

446
00:53:50,280 --> 00:53:52,280
 but I think there was an aggregate demand problem.

447
00:53:52,280 --> 00:53:59,280
 And I think one of the problems was certainly that there was not a proper transmission of monetary policy,

448
00:53:59,280 --> 00:54:04,280
 because the banking system in some European countries was in a rather bad shape.

449
00:54:04,280 --> 00:54:09,280
 And I think it's a country that both of us, well, you more than me, know relatively well, among others.

450
00:54:09,280 --> 00:54:13,280
 So I think, again, I want to kind of focus here really on the financial stability side,

451
00:54:13,280 --> 00:54:19,280
 that might also take a role of why it hasn't always worked as it was supposed to work.

452
00:54:19,280 --> 00:54:26,280
 Let me, maybe one more remark before I go to my next set of comments.

453
00:54:26,280 --> 00:54:34,280
 Yes, going forward, I mean, we have now new types of shocks, and basically started with the pandemic.

454
00:54:34,280 --> 00:54:40,280
 Of course, then the invasion of Ukraine by Russia, energy price shocks, and so on.

455
00:54:40,280 --> 00:54:47,280
 And of course, with the climate change, maybe the demographic change, there might be a tendency towards higher inflation, actually.

456
00:54:47,280 --> 00:54:55,280
 So this whole more shock-filled world of poly-crisis might, of course, also kind of introduce an upside risk to that.

457
00:54:55,280 --> 00:55:03,280
 Now, Veteran has already taken a little bit away my punch point, punch line, by mentioning macro-potential policy.

458
00:55:03,280 --> 00:55:07,280
 Because I would have expected, actually, Claudio, that you would mention it.

459
00:55:07,280 --> 00:55:16,280
 Because if you think about monetary and financial stability as two goals that are not completely correlated with each other,

460
00:55:16,280 --> 00:55:21,280
 then according to the Tinbergen rule, we also would need a second, another tool.

461
00:55:21,280 --> 00:55:26,280
 And we know that micro-potential supervision, regulation supervision is not sufficient for that.

462
00:55:26,280 --> 00:55:32,280
 So I think there, the macro-potential policy, and I would very much like to get a view on that,

463
00:55:32,280 --> 00:55:39,280
 that I think can have a very important role in terms of kind of dampening somewhat the financial crisis.

464
00:55:39,280 --> 00:55:45,280
 Or maybe make the damage, mitigate the damage that I mentioned earlier by, of course, by inflation targeting.

465
00:55:45,280 --> 00:55:48,280
 Now, I didn't, I don't mean this, not seriously, but ironic.

466
00:55:48,280 --> 00:55:56,280
 So, and I think, I mean, we're talking, of course, mostly here about the time series dimension of micro-potential policies,

467
00:55:56,280 --> 00:56:03,280
 or the counter-capital buffer and the kind of, yeah, reducing the financial cycles.

468
00:56:03,280 --> 00:56:09,280
 Now, there, I think, we still have to learn a lot.

469
00:56:09,280 --> 00:56:15,280
 Because it's, at least here in Europe, it's still relatively new, the micro-potential policy.

470
00:56:15,280 --> 00:56:23,280
 And, of course, we also learn that it's, it might work very differently when a financial cycle is kind of indulgently caused.

471
00:56:23,280 --> 00:56:30,280
 So between boom, credit boom and bust, rather than responding to an exhaustion shock like the pandemic, for example.

472
00:56:30,280 --> 00:56:36,280
 Now, here actually, let me also mention, coming back to these unconventional risks,

473
00:56:36,280 --> 00:56:43,280
 I think also the new, the next challenge for financial stability and ultimately for macro-potential policy

474
00:56:43,280 --> 00:56:47,280
 will be these new types of shocks that we are increasingly seeing.

475
00:56:47,280 --> 00:56:52,280
 So, because, of course, the macro-potential policy framework that was put in place in Europe,

476
00:56:52,280 --> 00:56:57,280
 as any regulatory reform was in response to the previous crisis, not fighting the next crisis.

477
00:56:57,280 --> 00:57:01,280
 But now we're seeing these new types of shocks, or again, you can call them supply-side shocks.

478
00:57:01,280 --> 00:57:06,280
 And actually, at the European Systemic Risk Board, they're doing some work exactly on kind of how to model it,

479
00:57:06,280 --> 00:57:11,280
 how to think about these risks and how they can influence the financial system.

480
00:57:11,280 --> 00:57:19,280
 The last comment I'd like to make is, you kind of mentioned this en passant at the very end,

481
00:57:19,280 --> 00:57:21,280
 but I think it's a very critical point.

482
00:57:21,280 --> 00:57:24,280
 It's something actually discussed briefly over lunch.

483
00:57:24,280 --> 00:57:30,280
 I think inflation targeting, as a necessary condition, has the independence of the central bank.

484
00:57:30,280 --> 00:57:37,280
 And I think that is where, I mean, on the other side of the Atlantic, that's clearly under threat right now, I would argue.

485
00:57:37,280 --> 00:57:44,280
 And it's a broader question, not just, I mean, we've seen those in other countries, of course.

486
00:57:44,280 --> 00:57:46,280
 Turkey is the best example, I would say.

487
00:57:46,280 --> 00:57:53,280
 Here in the Euro area, we're kind of, I would say, blessed, because we have the, I guess, the most independent central bank in the world.

488
00:57:53,280 --> 00:57:54,280
 Do we?

489
00:57:54,280 --> 00:57:57,280
 I'm not sure, as you would agree, yes.

490
00:57:57,280 --> 00:57:58,280
 It's pretty independent, I would say.

491
00:57:58,280 --> 00:58:00,280
 So there is no immediate threat.

492
00:58:00,280 --> 00:58:06,280
 But there is a threat, I would also say, from populist policies, politicians, sorry, populist politicians,

493
00:58:06,280 --> 00:58:09,280
 that kind of want to attack the ECB for all kind of reasons.

494
00:58:09,280 --> 00:58:13,280
 In the Euro debt crisis, because ECB was actually sitting on the wrong side of the table.

495
00:58:13,280 --> 00:58:16,280
 It shouldn't have sat with the EDIMF.

496
00:58:16,280 --> 00:58:18,280
 Was also a crisis manager, suddenly.

497
00:58:18,280 --> 00:58:22,280
 Or in Germany, because the interest rates were too low, or next time it's going to be, again,

498
00:58:22,280 --> 00:58:26,280
 maybe some southern countries, or who knows who's going to complain about them.

499
00:58:26,280 --> 00:58:35,280
 So constant attacks against, political attacks against the credibility, can also undermine the credibility of a central bank, I would argue.

500
00:58:35,280 --> 00:58:39,280
 Not to mean, of course, there is a degree of accountability.

501
00:58:39,280 --> 00:58:45,280
 So, of course, on the other side of the Atlantic, the independence is much more directly under threat.

502
00:58:45,280 --> 00:58:51,280
 And here, I would say, this might also have a, might be a challenge for the future of inflation targeting.

503
00:58:51,280 --> 00:58:59,280
 How do we think about this in a world where there is, number one, much more, much more of these unconventional shocks that I mentioned.

504
00:58:59,280 --> 00:59:05,280
 Much more political interference from governments inside, outside the country.

505
00:59:05,280 --> 00:59:16,280
 And how to manage then, both the communication side, but in the actual decision side, I think it's going to be somewhat pretty tricky going forward.

506
00:59:16,280 --> 00:59:22,280
 Having said all of this, again, I'm very thankful that you have put this together, and having been able to read it, and thank you again.

507
00:59:22,280 --> 00:59:35,280
 Okay, so I suggest that Claudio now responds to these comments.

