00:59:53,280 --> 01:00:02,280
 I won't go through all of them, but just a few points of clarification and so on.

514
01:00:02,280 --> 01:00:03,280
 Structural factors are not important.

515
01:00:03,280 --> 01:00:16,280
 I'm not saying that they're not important necessarily, but what I'm definitely saying is that it would be useful when thinking about our star people actually and their determinants.

516
01:00:16,280 --> 01:00:20,280
 They also looked a little bit more closely at the data, and they allowed the data to speak.

517
01:00:20,280 --> 01:00:32,280
 If you think, for example, of demographics, I mean, most of the evidence that we have about the demographic, the impact of the demographic itself, is that, well, you have a model.

518
01:00:32,280 --> 01:00:40,280
 It basically says demographics is important, and then based on that model that says the demographics is important, you say, oh, look at this.

519
01:00:40,280 --> 01:00:45,280
 Actually, it seems to be tracing pretty well what's happened to our star.

520
01:00:45,280 --> 01:00:46,280
 And, of course, everyone is doing that.

521
01:00:46,280 --> 01:00:55,280
 There's a lot of calibration of that type, so our star gets, becomes completely over-determined if you start looking at those models.

522
01:00:55,280 --> 01:01:02,280
 So what I'm saying is a lot of the evidence about our star is sort of, is of a circular nature.

523
01:01:02,280 --> 01:01:11,280
 You either embed the assumption in the estimation of our star, that's, for example, the Laubach-Williams methodology.

524
01:01:11,280 --> 01:01:15,280
 You know what is being driven by, plus some unobserved factors.

525
01:01:15,280 --> 01:01:21,280
 So growth is important in the model, and that's going to, because it's important to the extent that it is there, it's going to be driving it.

526
01:01:21,280 --> 01:01:25,280
 And then there are some unobserved factors on top of that.

527
01:01:25,280 --> 01:01:31,280
 Or is of the kind of calibration type that I've basically suggested.

528
01:01:31,280 --> 01:01:33,280
 You assume that the model is right.

529
01:01:33,280 --> 01:01:41,280
 You calibrate the model and say, assuming that this model is right, then this is basically why it is, why we see what we see.

530
01:01:41,280 --> 01:01:50,280
 And the other extraordinary thing about most of this, particularly these model type analysis that look at demographics, income distribution, or whatever,

531
01:01:50,280 --> 01:01:54,280
 is that they're doing it from the 1980s onwards.

532
01:01:54,280 --> 01:01:57,280
 But they don't apply, they don't look at whatever happened earlier.

533
01:01:57,280 --> 01:02:03,280
 And, of course, over, since the 1980s, interest rates have been trending down.

534
01:02:03,280 --> 01:02:07,280
 And lo and behold, they started with a huge Volcker shock.

535
01:02:07,280 --> 01:02:11,280
 So that was, that's where the starting of the period is.

536
01:02:11,280 --> 01:02:17,280
 If you go further back and you try and say, okay, let's look at demographics, let's look at income distribution, let's look at growth.

537
01:02:17,280 --> 01:02:20,280
 Actually, the link, the systematic link is not there.

538
01:02:20,280 --> 01:02:24,280
 It is only the extraordinary, I was a bit surprised to see it.

539
01:02:24,280 --> 01:02:30,280
 But actually, it is, if there is a robust link, unfortunately, this is what the data show, the link is with monetary policy.

540
01:02:30,280 --> 01:02:38,280
 Which is why I sort of suggested what I was, what I was suggesting in terms of the, how do we interpret that, that kind of evidence.

541
01:02:38,280 --> 01:02:39,280
 Point targets.

542
01:02:39,280 --> 01:02:40,280
 Point targets.

543
01:02:40,280 --> 01:02:54,280
 I think it's, whether you have a point target or whether you have a band, it's less important than, if you like, your reaction function.

544
01:02:54,280 --> 01:03:09,280
 And to me, the key of what I was trying to say, which is, again, is not, I think is widely shared, but if anything, your reaction function should be, if inflation goes up, then you react quickly and strongly.

545
01:03:09,280 --> 01:03:18,280
 But if it's sort of, and a few basis points, 50 basis points, one percentage point below, even a point target, don't worry too much, because it's not going to get out of control.

546
01:03:18,280 --> 01:03:24,280
 So react less and try to keep your room for maneuver for when time really matters.

547
01:03:24,280 --> 01:03:36,280
 Modeling framework, sure, models, I mean, if we had another model today and so on, models are, for me, what is more important about the model is the way of thinking behind it.

548
01:03:36,280 --> 01:03:49,280
 And I think that there is a big difference, if you expect the economy to be driven by exogenous shocks, basically then propagate and then the economy then returns to a steady state,

549
01:03:49,280 --> 01:03:55,280
 versus a situation in which you have endogenous financial, endogenous contractions and expansions of economic activities, a way of thinking.

550
01:03:55,280 --> 01:04:06,280
 What struck me over the years, when I was at the BIS, is that when I was talking to macroeconomists, the only way that they could think about the economy working over that period of time,

551
01:04:06,280 --> 01:04:13,280
 which is against also the history of economic thought, if you like, was in terms of these exogenous shocks.

552
01:04:13,280 --> 01:04:18,280
 And then the economy would return to equilibrium, so that if you think about the great financial crisis,

553
01:04:18,280 --> 01:04:25,280
 well, that was either people all of a sudden deciding to, it was a consumption shock, all of a sudden people decided to consume less,

554
01:04:25,280 --> 01:04:28,280
 or it was a productivity shock coming from nowhere.

555
01:04:28,280 --> 01:04:33,280
 Well, this is not really what happened, I think it's pretty obvious.

556
01:04:33,280 --> 01:04:39,280
 But then over time, when central banks developed their financial stability side,

557
01:04:39,280 --> 01:04:43,280
 then those working on the financial stability side would actually have a completely different paradigm,

558
01:04:43,280 --> 01:04:50,280
 which is indeed the financial cycle, which has become part of the furniture of economic thinking on that part of the central bank.

559
01:04:50,280 --> 01:04:58,280
 So you had even within the central bank, many, in a vast economy, central banks in particular, I would say like two different schools of thought.

560
01:04:58,280 --> 01:05:07,280
 Those that were thinking in terms of these DSG type models, and those who were thinking in terms of this financial, less structural sort of models.

561
01:05:07,280 --> 01:05:14,280
 And I think what we need is, I think we need to merge those two, merge those two traditions.

562
01:05:14,280 --> 01:05:21,280
 So turning to Torsten now, I hope that's okay, turning to Torsten.

563
01:05:21,280 --> 01:05:31,280
 Well, actually I was not saying that the reason why we had the financial booms and so on was because our star was falling.

564
01:05:31,280 --> 01:05:35,280
 I was actually saying that it was largely the result of the central bank reaction function.

565
01:05:35,280 --> 01:05:43,280
 And indeed the risk taking channel, actually it was with a colleague of mine that we introduced the idea many, many years ago.

566
01:05:43,280 --> 01:05:47,280
 And I remember at the time, actually it was at an ECB conference.

567
01:05:47,280 --> 01:05:52,280
 I remember that the first reaction that I had to that paper at that conference was,

568
01:05:52,280 --> 01:05:56,280
 "What the heck is this risk taking channel? It doesn't make any sense."

569
01:05:56,280 --> 01:06:01,280
 Or he made discussions with Lars Venson. I mean, it was always really very funny with him.

570
01:06:01,280 --> 01:06:07,280
 He just couldn't understand that it was possible there was any such thing as a risk taking channel of monetary policy.

571
01:06:07,280 --> 01:06:12,280
 I think the risk taking channel is part of the story, but it's clearly not the whole story.

572
01:06:12,280 --> 01:06:23,280
 The financial system being broken post-GFC, absolutely. I mean, particularly during what I would call the recovery phase.

573
01:06:23,280 --> 01:06:28,280
 You had to fix the financial system if you wanted monetary policy to have traction.

574
01:06:28,280 --> 01:06:30,280
 That's a lesson that we know from history.

575
01:06:30,280 --> 01:06:36,280
 But my point is that even once the financial system got fixed and central banks were trying,

576
01:06:36,280 --> 01:06:42,280
 inflation was at 1.5, 1.7, we've got to get it to 2 and we've got to do whatever it takes to take it to 2.

577
01:06:42,280 --> 01:06:46,280
 That's the kind of mentality that I think was problematic.

578
01:06:46,280 --> 01:06:48,280
 Macroprudential policy.

579
01:06:48,280 --> 01:06:52,280
 Well, I mean, again, you're pushing on an open door because, I mean,

580
01:06:52,280 --> 01:06:57,280
 we developed this macroprudential stuff at the BIS many, many, many years ago.

581
01:06:57,280 --> 01:07:04,280
 But the problem there is that, at least the way that we thought about it when we were working on it,

582
01:07:04,280 --> 01:07:09,280
 and, again, sort of advocating it when no one really cared,

583
01:07:09,280 --> 01:07:15,280
 was precisely that you had to think of these two things,

584
01:07:15,280 --> 01:07:18,280
 monetary policy and macroprudential policy together.

585
01:07:18,280 --> 01:07:21,280
 That, if you like, the financial cycle was so powerful

586
01:07:21,280 --> 01:07:24,280
 that just relying on one of the two instruments to deal with it

587
01:07:24,280 --> 01:07:27,280
 would be completely unbalanced and would not work.

588
01:07:27,280 --> 01:07:31,280
 So my presentation was about what was about inflation targeting

589
01:07:31,280 --> 01:07:36,280
 and they are references to macroprudential, but they are in the background.

590
01:07:36,280 --> 01:07:40,280
 But the key point here is that the two things have to work hand in hand

591
01:07:40,280 --> 01:07:43,280
 in order to have a balanced response to this financial example.

592
01:07:43,280 --> 01:07:46,280
 And, moreover, you do also need the macroprudential policy

593
01:07:46,280 --> 01:07:52,280
 to be based on a strong microprudential foundation.

594
01:07:52,280 --> 01:07:57,280
 And, actually, what worried me following:

595
01:07:57,280 --> 01:08:03,280
 Look, great financial crisis, G20, the new kid on the block.

596
01:08:03,280 --> 01:08:06,280
 They basically wrote this wonderful report basically saying

597
01:08:06,280 --> 01:08:08,280
 macroprudential has to be the way we go.

598
01:08:08,280 --> 01:08:10,280
 And, you know, for people like me at the BIS, that was great.

599
01:08:10,280 --> 01:08:11,280
 Huge success.

600
01:08:11,280 --> 01:08:14,280
 And, then I started having second thoughts about it

601
01:08:14,280 --> 01:08:18,280
 because I realised that this was giving central banks a reason to say

602
01:08:18,280 --> 01:08:23,280
 central banks were becoming increasingly, not enthusiastically,

603
01:08:23,280 --> 01:08:25,280
 but increasingly sort of shifting to the same,

604
01:08:25,280 --> 01:08:27,280
 well, monetary policy has something to do with this

605
01:08:27,280 --> 01:08:30,280
 and needs to take part of the, needs to be part of the response

606
01:08:30,280 --> 01:08:35,280
 to the financial cycle, to, oh, God, now we've got macroprudential policy,

607
01:08:35,280 --> 01:08:39,280
 it's business as usual, we can continue doing things as we were doing before.

608
01:08:39,280 --> 01:08:44,280
 And, I think that was part of the, part of the issue.

609
01:08:44,280 --> 01:08:49,280
 And, looking forward, you mentioned that there are new shocks

610
01:08:49,280 --> 01:08:52,280
 that macroprudential policy needs to address.

611
01:08:52,280 --> 01:08:55,280
 I think, I'm not sure you mentioned it explicitly,

612
01:08:55,280 --> 01:09:00,280
 but I think it's the biggest issue, which, which has to do,

613
01:09:00,280 --> 01:09:04,280
 and it's very hard to address, which is basically fiscal.

614
01:09:04,280 --> 01:09:07,280
 The unsustainability of the fiscal positions.

615
01:09:07,280 --> 01:09:12,280
 Because, you know, the government is always the sort of,

616
01:09:12,280 --> 01:09:15,280
 the one who provides solvency of last resort,

617
01:09:15,280 --> 01:09:17,280
 but if the government itself is insolvent,

618
01:09:17,280 --> 01:09:19,280
 you're going to have huge problems.

619
01:09:19,280 --> 01:09:21,280
 And, because of a number of reasons,

620
01:09:21,280 --> 01:09:23,280
 it's very, very difficult to deal with that.

621
01:09:23,280 --> 01:09:27,280
 But, I think that's the next frontier of macroprudential policy.

622
01:09:27,280 --> 01:09:29,280
 I've written a paper with a colleague of mine on that,

623
01:09:29,280 --> 01:09:33,280
 but the answers are very, sort of, they're not clear-cut at all

624
01:09:33,280 --> 01:09:35,280
 because of this fundamental asymmetry.

625
01:09:35,280 --> 01:09:41,280
 That fiscal policy is the ultimate backstop to the financial system to start with.

626
01:09:41,280 --> 01:09:45,280
 And this, of course, is also related to central bank independence going forward.

627
01:09:45,280 --> 01:09:48,280
 It is going to be a huge problem.

628
01:09:48,280 --> 01:09:49,280
 Okay.

629
01:09:49,280 --> 01:09:50,280
 Thank you.

630
01:09:50,280 --> 01:09:56,280
 So, let's start with Steve Trichetti and Chris Poppa and Michael Kumhoff.

631
01:09:56,280 --> 01:09:59,280
 And then we'll do the next round.

632
01:09:59,280 --> 01:10:00,280
 Yeah.

633
01:10:00,280 --> 01:10:01,280
 Thanks very, thanks very much.

634
01:10:01,280 --> 01:10:09,280
 So, first of all, I want to compliment Claudio on actually succeeding in being somewhat optimistic,

635
01:10:09,280 --> 01:10:16,280
 which I know is not really his natural state, after years of working together.

636
01:10:16,280 --> 01:10:17,280
 He's trying.

637
01:10:17,280 --> 01:10:18,280
 You're trying.

638
01:10:18,280 --> 01:10:29,280
 I think that, and so in that sense I would be, I think that your paper and your presentation are capable of being read as being very optimistic,

639
01:10:29,280 --> 01:10:32,280
 which is that this is a good framework.

640
01:10:32,280 --> 01:10:33,280
 It works.

641
01:10:33,280 --> 01:10:36,280
 Let's refine it in order to make it better.

642
01:10:36,280 --> 01:10:39,280
 And if we can do that, that would be great.

643
01:10:39,280 --> 01:10:41,280
 But let me question that.

644
01:10:41,280 --> 01:10:46,280
 So, Torsten mentioned the problem of populist politicians.

645
01:10:46,280 --> 01:10:55,280
 And one of the ways of reading what's happened in recent years is that people care not about inflation.

646
01:10:55,280 --> 01:10:57,280
 Nobody understands inflation.

647
01:10:57,280 --> 01:10:59,280
 They care about price levels.

648
01:10:59,280 --> 01:11:05,280
 And when price levels go up, then if you say, oh, I'm inflation targeting and inflation is going to come down,

649
01:11:05,280 --> 01:11:07,280
 what they hear is something else.

650
01:11:07,280 --> 01:11:09,280
 They hear that price levels are going to come down.

651
01:11:09,280 --> 01:11:18,280
 Because they're victims of price level increases while they are somehow, they're deserving of wage increases.

652
01:11:18,280 --> 01:11:25,280
 And so my question for you is whether or not we've actually formulated the objective properly,

653
01:11:25,280 --> 01:11:32,280
 given the political economy risks that we seem to face if we actually do inflation targeting.

654
01:11:32,280 --> 01:11:39,280
 Because it's great to have low inflation, but what's not great is to have inflation that's occasionally high.

655
01:11:39,280 --> 01:11:42,280
 I think he's going to want to go a couple more.

656
01:11:42,280 --> 01:11:43,280
 Chris?

657
01:11:43,280 --> 01:11:45,280
 Thank you.

658
01:11:45,280 --> 01:11:46,280
 Oh, Chris.

659
01:11:46,280 --> 01:11:58,280
 I will join in the chorus of congratulations for Claudio's presentation and very quickly telegraph four points across their complement and I think may even elicit a response.

660
01:11:58,280 --> 01:12:02,280
 The first one is the fact that there is a commonality.

661
01:12:02,280 --> 01:12:17,280
 is clearly that we don't have any competing monetary policy regime right now to basically credibly claim that it would perform better and therefore it would be a substitution away from inflation targeting.

662
01:12:17,280 --> 01:12:23,280
 But inflation targeting being this broad kind of church does have different flavors.

663
01:12:23,280 --> 01:12:33,280
 And I would like to recall one that was actually part of the, let's say, publications of the BIS I think about eight years ago.

664
01:12:33,280 --> 01:12:37,280
 The idea of more broadly defined and flexible inflation targeting.

665
01:12:37,280 --> 01:12:54,280
 Now when we tried to do this in Romania in about 2006-07, in the middle of a huge deluge of forex, essentially lending investment and general portfolio investment, that was a problem in itself.

666
01:12:54,280 --> 01:13:09,280
 And we defined the objective right at that point in time as achieving the inflation goals sustainably over the medium term, but not at the cost of sacrificing any basic macro balance or worsening financial stability risks.

667
01:13:09,280 --> 01:13:21,280
 And I think that that could be a good heuristic because you, the temptation to broaden things is there, but there is a limit to how much you can include in this spot that it still makes policy sense and is tractable.

668
01:13:21,280 --> 01:13:22,280
 That's the first thing.

669
01:13:22,280 --> 01:13:26,280
 The second one is the friends we didn't make, but we actually lost along the way.

670
01:13:26,280 --> 01:13:36,280
 I think the way policy formulation for inflation targeting started, it basically spoke about using all available instruments to achieve the inflation targets.

671
01:13:36,280 --> 01:13:39,280
 We seem to now be fixated on the policy rate.

672
01:13:39,280 --> 01:13:49,280
 And I would posit that there is a role to be played by a foreign exchange policy and by controversially liquidity interventions,

673
01:13:49,280 --> 01:13:55,280
 depending on how intelligently these are applied and how they respond to multiple objectives.

674
01:13:55,280 --> 01:14:03,280
 The third thing would be is that you made a very good point and this I find is one of the sources of tension and preoccupation for me.

675
01:14:03,280 --> 01:14:11,280
 Monetary policy and inflation targeting environment makes sense to be formulated, implemented and then appraised in the medium run.

676
01:14:11,280 --> 01:14:17,280
 But the temptation is to basically do so in a very myopic short-term setting.

677
01:14:17,280 --> 01:14:33,280
 And this coupled with the misbehaviour of fiscal and the permanent, it seems, policy challenges posed by fragile independence for central banks are a source of preoccupation.

678
01:14:33,280 --> 01:14:42,280
 I don't have an answer for this, but I do have a second thought, which is sometimes the central bank can be seen as too much of a solution.

679
01:14:42,280 --> 01:14:48,280
 Think of, for example, of the temptation of saying, oh, loose fiscal, the solution is tight monetary.

680
01:14:48,280 --> 01:14:55,280
 Well, what that leads to is a massive unsustainable appreciation of a flexible exchange rate.

681
01:14:55,280 --> 01:15:01,280
 And therefore it creates more risks and more problems for the economy than it solves.

682
01:15:01,280 --> 01:15:09,280
 So we should be mindful of how we formulate this without pretending that it actually solves the problem outright.

683
01:15:09,280 --> 01:15:12,280
 Now, my final point is the following.

684
01:15:12,280 --> 01:15:20,280
 We seem to assume that communication of inflation targeting processes to the public is always appropriate.

685
01:15:20,280 --> 01:15:33,280
 I'm not saying it's not, but one of the things I'm tempted to favor is that as we move to increasingly complex and less transparent for outside observers models,

686
01:15:33,280 --> 01:15:43,280
 there is a strong case that central banks should increasingly basically go for staff level projections and risk assessment

687
01:15:43,280 --> 01:15:51,280
 and leave the board to do what it can do better, which is basically to say, yes, I mean the staff is saying this, we disagree, we'd like to add more color here.

688
01:15:51,280 --> 01:15:56,280
 We would reformulate this and we would basically draw in a broader perspective.

689
01:15:56,280 --> 01:15:58,280
 Again, thank you very much for the presentation.

690
01:15:58,280 --> 01:16:07,280
 I think it's a very valuable long-term assessment of what used to be controversial back in the 90s.

691
01:16:07,280 --> 01:16:08,280
 Thank you.

692
01:16:08,280 --> 01:16:14,280
 And now Michael Kumhoff and then you can respond and then we'll have another round.

693
01:16:14,280 --> 01:16:17,280
 Thank you.

694
01:16:17,280 --> 01:16:22,280
 I only have one question, but to me it's the elephant in the room.

695
01:16:22,280 --> 01:16:32,280
 You were saying that monetary policy determines or at the very least co-determines the real interest rate, R-star.

696
01:16:32,280 --> 01:16:35,280
 And I completely agree with you.

697
01:16:35,280 --> 01:16:47,280
 Now, if that is the case, monetary policy makes a big real decision that's on a par with what fiscal policy does in terms of making real decisions.

698
01:16:47,280 --> 01:16:54,280
 Now, against that backdrop, what does that tell us about whether we should or should not have monetary policy independence?

699
01:16:54,280 --> 01:17:03,280
 Because that was thought about monetary policy independence was on the basis that the central bank only is about the price level, about nominal variables, etc.

700
01:17:03,280 --> 01:17:07,280
 But here it's about a real variable.

701
01:17:07,280 --> 01:17:09,280
 Thank you. So, Claudius?

702
01:17:09,280 --> 01:17:19,280
 Okay. So, first of all, Steve, yes, indeed, this is something that we have learned.

703
01:17:19,280 --> 01:17:26,280
 Maybe we should have known from the past, but I guess we're all very young.

704
01:17:26,280 --> 01:17:29,280
 Think about when inflation was there for the last time.

705
01:17:29,280 --> 01:17:36,280
 Is that people actually do care about the price level and for them, for at least many people, it's very hard to make a distinction between the two.

706
01:17:36,280 --> 01:17:41,280
 Of course, financial markets are very good at it, but not the households or possibly even workers.

707
01:17:41,280 --> 01:17:54,280
 By the way, as an aside, if anything, I'm actually surprised that wages have not adjusted more and regained more of the loss in purchasing power that they have lost given all of that.

708
01:17:54,280 --> 01:18:06,280
 My answer to that is that if the implication of what you said is that we should move to price level targeting, because that's what people care about,

709
01:18:06,280 --> 01:18:13,280
 that's one way in which one could read the statement, then that would actually be, over time, even less credible for the reasons that we know.

710
01:18:13,280 --> 01:18:23,280
 You know, bygones are bygones. Once you have to induce a recession because the price level had gone up in the past, I don't think that people would take it lightly.

711
01:18:23,280 --> 01:18:29,280
 Nothing much may happen to prices, but once the economy tanks, then the central bank would be blamed.

712
01:18:29,280 --> 01:18:42,280
 So I don't think that can be the answer. So the best, second best, if you like, or third best, is basically to aim for a low level of inflation.

713
01:18:42,280 --> 01:18:52,280
 But again, with this, you know, to me, inflation is almost like a state of mind that a precise number is, like inflation being low enough so that you don't really care so much about it.

714
01:18:52,280 --> 01:19:04,280
 Because my price level is going to be different from your price level. As a producer, the price that I care about is going to be different from the prices that others care about because wages are not going to be, which are the common factor.

715
01:19:04,280 --> 01:19:21,280
 Because we have many of these price changes are not going to be that important. So that, I think, is the second best world that we can deal with or is realistically possible, given how people think about it and what people care.

716
01:19:21,280 --> 01:19:31,280
 People care about the price level, but they also, of course, care about their employment, if their employment disappears. So from a political economy perspective, I think it's very hard.

717
01:19:31,280 --> 01:19:59,280
 And they're only second best solutions. A number of the big church, yes, absolutely. And I think that if there is one word of what you said that I fully subscribe to, I mean, many things that what you said that I fully subscribe to, including this idea that it doesn't need to be just one instrument and so on and so forth, and the role of the exchange rate as well in that context.

718
01:19:59,280 --> 01:20:12,280
 Of course, with the exchange rate is that to the extent that you're using it, there is the N minus one problem, right? That the anchor country in the world somehow has to have something which is not based on the exchange rate.

719
01:20:12,280 --> 01:20:28,280
 But I think that going back, I think what is key is really the issue of the sustainability of the regime. And everything, whenever I think about something, I think what is sustainable over time. And that's why I said, you know, the long horizons being,

720
01:20:28,280 --> 01:20:45,280
 is very important in any policy that you put in place. Fiscal and monetary policy, well, that goes back to what I, to a remark I have at the end about not much monetary policy can do if fiscal policy is out of culture.

721
01:20:45,280 --> 01:21:04,280
 The question of the issue, or the concept of the region of stability that we put forward in the annual economic report a couple of years ago, whereby most monetary and fiscal policy have to be within a certain range, which is, of course, hard to define, if you want to have sustainable economic performance.

722
01:21:04,280 --> 01:21:11,280
 So, yes, and unfortunately, there's not much monetary policy can do if fiscal policy is completely out of whack.

723
01:21:11,280 --> 01:21:21,280
 And Michael, first of all, there are two ways of answering your question. Well, there are three.

724
01:21:21,280 --> 01:21:32,280
 One, of course, is that the idea that monetary policy can only affect nominal variables is a little bit of a sort of straw man.

725
01:21:32,280 --> 01:21:39,280
 And, of course, it can be useful for communication purposes, but also one has to take it with a pinch of salt.

726
01:21:39,280 --> 01:21:47,280
 But quite apart from that, the way in which I was thinking of affecting our star, I don't like the concept very much.

727
01:21:47,280 --> 01:22:00,280
 But anyway, the way affecting our star was, look, over time, if you contribute to a big financial cycle, then you will end up with very low interest rates for very long, in real terms, too.

728
01:22:00,280 --> 01:22:05,280
 And so it's only over a very, very long horizon that you have affected it.

729
01:22:05,280 --> 01:22:07,280
 Are you changing our star?

730
01:22:07,280 --> 01:22:11,280
 It depends on your model and your definition of our star.

731
01:22:11,280 --> 01:22:17,280
 You're definitely going to have, as a result, very low interest rates for a long time in order to revive the economy.

732
01:22:17,280 --> 01:22:25,280
 The other way of thinking about it is that, well, within a range, as I said, it doesn't really matter when it comes to real economic activity and possibly inflation.

733
01:22:25,280 --> 01:22:27,280
 It has a big impact on the financial system.

734
01:22:27,280 --> 01:22:34,280
 But for the real economic activity and for inflation, maybe you can have interest rates, real interest rates within a range.

735
01:22:34,280 --> 01:22:42,280
 And that is roughly going to be consistent with different outcomes in, or the same outcome for output and for inflation.

736
01:22:42,280 --> 01:22:44,280
 Okay, thank you.

737
01:22:44,280 --> 01:22:50,280
 Next, Ricardo, Federico, Maria Cecilia, gentleman over there.

738
01:22:50,280 --> 01:22:53,280
 And at the end, Anastasios.

739
01:22:53,280 --> 01:22:56,280
 Thanks, Claudio, for the presentation.

740
01:22:56,280 --> 01:23:08,280
 There is now several papers from John Williams, Fed of New York, on our double star.

741
01:23:08,280 --> 01:23:10,280
 I don't know if you've seen them.

742
01:23:10,280 --> 01:23:20,280
 So they're doing research saying that financial stability is not in Taylor's equation.

743
01:23:20,280 --> 01:23:24,280
 So now we're going to create another one, is double star.

744
01:23:24,280 --> 01:23:29,280
 So different economies, each economies has its own eye star.

745
01:23:29,280 --> 01:23:34,280
 You know, beauty is in the eyes of the beholder, as the English say.

746
01:23:34,280 --> 01:23:36,280
 And now there is not only one star.

747
01:23:36,280 --> 01:23:43,280
 There is another constellation, which is the R double star, which is financial stability.

748
01:23:43,280 --> 01:24:00,280
 There is an article that has been on shelf after the financial crisis, which is Armin Altian and Ben Klein, 1973, Journal of Money, Credit and Banking, on the correct measurement of inflation.

749
01:24:00,280 --> 01:24:18,280
 And that brings the issue that Torsten raised, of whether the Taylor rule has been effective in delivering inflation, low and stable inflation, but whether also has been the cause of financial bubbles.

750
01:24:18,280 --> 01:24:28,280
 And that's the issue that was raised by Altian and Allen, who were my professors at UCLA at graduate school.

751
01:24:28,280 --> 01:24:35,280
 So my question to you, Claudio, is what about other approaches?

752
01:24:35,280 --> 01:24:44,280
 I know it's difficult to implement the nominal GDP targeting.

753
01:24:44,280 --> 01:24:51,280
 So what's your view on that?

754
01:24:51,280 --> 01:24:58,280
 And I am a believer that quantities are exogenous and prices are endogenous.

755
01:24:58,280 --> 01:25:07,280
 And the interest rate, both the whole curve of terms, but also the very short one, the policy rate, is a price.

756
01:25:07,280 --> 01:25:09,280
 It's the most important price in the economy.

757
01:25:09,280 --> 01:25:11,280
 It's the price between the future and the present.

758
01:25:11,280 --> 01:25:15,280
 Shouldn't it be endogenous rather than the instrument of...

759
01:25:15,280 --> 01:25:16,280
 So what are your views on this?

760
01:25:16,280 --> 01:25:17,280
 Yes, please.

761
01:25:17,280 --> 01:25:18,280
 No, okay.

762
01:25:18,280 --> 01:25:19,280
 So, please, Mario.

763
01:25:19,280 --> 01:25:20,280
 Yeah, hi.

764
01:25:20,280 --> 01:25:24,280
 Thank you very much for the presentation and the discussion so far.

765
01:25:24,280 --> 01:25:39,280
 My question is, is your analysis really applicable to inflation targeting by all central banks?

766
01:25:39,280 --> 01:25:44,280
 Or did you share a distinctly European perspective with us?

767
01:25:44,280 --> 01:25:52,280
 And how would you modify your analysis if you were to speak about central banks, like specific central banks, other than the ECB?

768
01:25:52,280 --> 01:25:53,280
 Thank you.

769
01:25:57,280 --> 01:25:58,280
 Thank you.

770
01:25:58,280 --> 01:25:59,280
 I'll be very brief.

771
01:25:59,280 --> 01:26:04,280
 I was struck by the things that you didn't say more than by the things you said.

772
01:26:04,280 --> 01:26:06,280
 And so two of them have been mentioned.

773
01:26:06,280 --> 01:26:09,280
 One is price level and the other is nominal GDP targeting.

774
01:26:09,280 --> 01:26:12,280
 The third you have not mentioned at all is climate.

775
01:26:12,280 --> 01:26:20,280
 Until recently, we had a president of the ECB who said that climate consideration should be part of the primary mandate of the ECB.

776
01:26:20,280 --> 01:26:26,280
 So, potentially overhauling entirely the inflation targeting framework.

777
01:26:26,280 --> 01:26:27,280
 I'd love to hear you on that.

778
01:26:27,280 --> 01:26:28,280
 Thank you.

779
01:26:28,280 --> 01:26:33,280
 Okay.

780
01:26:33,280 --> 01:26:35,280
 So, I think...

781
01:26:35,280 --> 01:26:37,280
 Okay.

782
01:26:37,280 --> 01:26:38,280
 Okay.

783
01:26:38,280 --> 01:26:39,280
 Okay.

784
01:26:39,280 --> 01:26:40,280
 So, that's it.

785
01:26:40,280 --> 01:26:41,280
 Okay.

786
01:26:41,280 --> 01:26:42,280
 Yeah.

787
01:26:42,280 --> 01:26:43,280
 Okay.

788
01:26:43,280 --> 01:26:44,280
 R double star.

789
01:26:44,280 --> 01:26:48,280
 If I recall, the paper on R double star had to do with...

790
01:26:48,280 --> 01:26:51,280
 It depends very much on the kind of model that you have.

791
01:26:51,280 --> 01:27:00,280
 And in that particular model, the R double star had a very sort of short-term focus on it, to it.

792
01:27:00,280 --> 01:27:07,280
 It was the idea that if you have problems in the financial system, your interest rate has to be even lower and so on.

793
01:27:07,280 --> 01:27:14,280
 Look, again, I would rather try to move away from this idea of R star.

794
01:27:14,280 --> 01:27:15,280
 Let me give you another example.

795
01:27:15,280 --> 01:27:18,280
 It all depends on how you think the economy works.

796
01:27:18,280 --> 01:27:30,280
 Larry Summers used to say that the R star was very, very low.

797
01:27:30,280 --> 01:27:33,280
 And that very, very low R star was creating bubbles.

798
01:27:33,280 --> 01:27:35,280
 It goes back to some of the...

799
01:27:35,280 --> 01:27:40,280
 And that was creating, you know, problems along the run for the economy.

800
01:27:40,280 --> 01:27:46,280
 Now, to me, that statement is almost a contradiction in terms.

801
01:27:46,280 --> 01:27:55,280
 If you think that R star is generating bubbles, if you think that that is having a big impact on the economy,

802
01:27:55,280 --> 01:28:02,280
 a destabilizing impact on the economy, then of course you can say that that R star in terms of how it is normally defined,

803
01:28:02,280 --> 01:28:05,280
 inflation and output period by period, then that's okay.

804
01:28:05,280 --> 01:28:14,280
 But over time, it means that it cannot be an equilibrium rate, because it is just generating a huge disequilibrium in the economy.

805
01:28:14,280 --> 01:28:23,280
 So, that goes back to the point that how, what R star is ultimately depends...

806
01:28:23,280 --> 01:28:29,280
 You can always define a concept which is R star, which is all else equal, conditional on all the other things that are there in the economy,

807
01:28:29,280 --> 01:28:34,280
 is going to be, is going to help you to reach your objectives.

808
01:28:34,280 --> 01:28:35,280
 Fine.

809
01:28:35,280 --> 01:28:38,280
 But that, to me, is going to be a very, very difficult concept to define.

810
01:28:38,280 --> 01:28:45,280
 It's going to be so model dependent that it's not going to be a particularly useful guide to policy.

811
01:28:45,280 --> 01:28:56,280
 The Alken article, yes, I remember reading it, it was about redefining the price index to include asset prices.

812
01:28:56,280 --> 01:28:59,280
 Yeah, exactly.

813
01:28:59,280 --> 01:29:02,280
 So, it's redefining the price index and so on.

814
01:29:02,280 --> 01:29:09,280
 I think that from an operational perspective, that would not be particularly helpful,

815
01:29:09,280 --> 01:29:15,280
 because the properties, say, the properties that property prices have, for example, are very, very different.

816
01:29:15,280 --> 01:29:21,280
 Statistical properties are very, very different from the properties that the normal price level has.

817
01:29:21,280 --> 01:29:33,280
 And if you are going to be including that as part of your index, you are going to likely generate a lot of instability in the economy.

818
01:29:33,280 --> 01:29:39,280
 That's why I am sort of more of the view that you have.

819
01:29:39,280 --> 01:29:43,280
 It's better to take what I call these financial imbalances into account.

820
01:29:43,280 --> 01:29:46,280
 Symptoms that the economy is out of whack.

821
01:29:46,280 --> 01:29:51,280
 And the financial side, including in that context property prices, which are actually key,

822
01:29:51,280 --> 01:29:57,280
 is going to come back and haunt you further down the road from your typical policy horizon.

823
01:29:57,280 --> 01:30:03,280
 Nominal inflation targeting, maybe.

824
01:30:03,280 --> 01:30:13,280
 But what I don't like, I don't think that typically when one talks about nominal inflation,

825
01:30:13,280 --> 01:30:20,280
 nominal income targeting, GDP targeting and so on, one is thinking of bygones not being bygones.

826
01:30:20,280 --> 01:30:29,280
 And if you add that to your system, if you think of that as nominal GDP targeting,

827
01:30:29,280 --> 01:30:37,280
 I don't think that those approaches are credible for the same reason that price level targeting is not credible.

828
01:30:37,280 --> 01:30:47,280
 I think that in general, the idea of giving more relevance in your framework to nominal variables and nominal quantities,

829
01:30:47,280 --> 01:30:54,280
 in addition to interest rates, as a guide to policy, is something that I think is worth exploring.

830
01:30:54,280 --> 01:30:59,280
 That's why I think that things going back to what you used to have at the ECB many years ago,

831
01:30:59,280 --> 01:31:06,280
 thinking of the role of monitoring credit aggregates, somehow bringing those in into your system,

832
01:31:06,280 --> 01:31:09,280
 your way of thinking about it is important.

833
01:31:09,280 --> 01:31:16,280
 And this also ties into the question of is what I have explained very much something for advanced economies.

834
01:31:16,280 --> 01:31:28,280
 Yeah, I would say that emerging market economies have also other issues to deal with,

835
01:31:28,280 --> 01:31:32,280
 that have to do with the foreign currency liabilities and so on and so forth.

836
01:31:32,280 --> 01:31:37,280
 And that means that I think all else equal, they're going to be given more weight to the exchange rate

837
01:31:37,280 --> 01:31:42,280
 than advanced economies central banks might, all else equal.

838
01:31:42,280 --> 01:31:44,280
 And I think that's relevant.

839
01:31:44,280 --> 01:31:49,280
 And I also think that the way that I tended to think about the whole thing at the BIS was so much,

840
01:31:49,280 --> 01:31:54,280
 we needed to think more of what we call a macro financial stability framework.

841
01:31:54,280 --> 01:32:00,280
 I think the IMF, I don't know where John is, talked about the integrated policy framework.

842
01:32:00,280 --> 01:32:02,280
 And it's that kind of thing.

843
01:32:02,280 --> 01:32:10,280
 You need to think of a variety of instruments to help you achieve longer term sustainable balance.

844
01:32:10,280 --> 01:32:16,280
 Climate, I would definitely would not add climate to monetary policy as an objective.

845
01:32:16,280 --> 01:32:22,280
 I think that also from a political economic, if that is what you suggested,

846
01:32:22,280 --> 01:32:29,280
 because from a political economic perspective, if anything is, would not work.

847
01:32:29,280 --> 01:32:36,280
 I think central banks should be, have as objective things that they can actually have a strong influence over

848
01:32:36,280 --> 01:32:42,280
 and they have the right tools to pursue and they don't get them into too many sort of complications,

849
01:32:42,280 --> 01:32:49,280
 political economic issues, and I think that climate change is one of them.

850
01:32:49,280 --> 01:32:53,280
 That's different from saying you've got a financial stability mandate

851
01:32:53,280 --> 01:32:58,280
 and you take climate change into account to the extent that that applies to your mandate,

852
01:32:58,280 --> 01:33:02,280
 or you've got an inflation objective, whatever other objective,

853
01:33:02,280 --> 01:33:05,280
 and you will take that into account in your policy decisions.

854
01:33:05,280 --> 01:33:10,280
 That's perfectly fine, because to the extent that it influences what you're responsible for.

855
01:33:11,280 --> 01:33:18,280
 Okay, thank you very much. I think we've had a fantastic keynote session.

856
01:33:18,280 --> 01:33:28,280
 Please, let's thank Claudio and our discussions.

857
01:33:28,280 --> 01:33:32,280
 We should be back in 15 minutes, right?

